  "summary": "Infinite blocks",
  "environment_raw": null,
  "description": "Blocks that are pushed by a piston when placed in creative mode will cause them to respawn after destruction and will not fall n n",
  "Steps to Reproduce": "1. Create a new Creative world with default settings.\n2. Enable cheats if necessary to access all blocks.\n3. Select a piston from the inventory.\n4. Place the piston facing any direction on the ground.\n5. Select a block that can be pushed by a piston (e.g., dirt, stone, or any non-indestructible block).\n6. Place the selected block directly in front of the piston.\n7. Activate the piston using a Redstone signal (e.g., place a Redstone Torch next to the piston).\n8. Observe the block being pushed by the piston.\n9. While the block is pushed, break the block with any tool or by hand.\n10. Wait for the block to respawn in the same position after it has been destroyed.\n11. Confirm that the block does not fall or behave as expected when destroyed.",
  "Environment": "Minecraft Java Edition Version 25w32a (snapshot)",
  "Observed Behavior": "When a block that is capable of being pushed by a piston is placed in Creative mode and subsequently destroyed, it will immediately respawn at its original location instead of dropping as an item. This behavior occurs regardless of the block type, as long as it is one that can be pushed by a piston (e.g., regular blocks like dirt, stone, etc.). \n\nAdditionally, these blocks do not exhibit gravity mechanics; they will not fall if the block beneath them is removed. Instead, they appear to be anchored in place, effectively creating an infinite supply of that block type. This issue can be replicated by performing the following steps:\n\n1. Enter Creative mode in a Minecraft world.\n2. Place a block that can be pushed by a piston (e.g., dirt).\n3. Use a piston to push the block.\n4. Destroy the block while it is being pushed.\n\nUpon destruction, the block will reappear at its original position instead of being removed from the game, leading to an infinite loop of block generation. This unintended behavior can disrupt gameplay and mechanics that rely on block destruction and gravity, such as redstone contraptions and building structures.",
  "Expected Behavior": "When a block is pushed by a piston in Creative mode, it should be destroyed and not respawn upon destruction. The block should behave according to standard game mechanics, where it is removed from the game world without reappearing. Additionally, if the block is a gravity-affected block (like sand or gravel), it should fall down to the block below it if there is no solid block supporting it. The intended behavior is that players can manipulate blocks freely in Creative mode without experiencing unintended respawning or falling issues.",
